{{notability|date=October 2013}} '''John W. Semple''' is a Canadian Scientist at [[St. Michael's Hospital (Toronto)|St. Michael's Hospital]] and a Professor of Pharmacology at the [[University of Toronto]]. He was born in [[Windsor, Ontario]] in 1959 and received his PhD in Immunology at [[Queen's University]] at [[Kingston, Ontario]]. In 1991, Semple, along with John Freedman, discovered a [[T helper cell]] defect in patients with the bleeding disorder called immune thrombocytopenic [[purpura]] (ITP).<ref>{{Cite journal | author = JW. Semple| title = Increased antiplatelet T helper lymphocyte reactivity in patients with autoimmune thrombocytopenia | journal = [[Blood (journal)|Blood]] | volume = 78 | pages = 2619–25 | year = 1991 | pmid = 1840468 | issue = 10 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> ITP is the condition of having a low [[platelet]] count (thrombocytopenia) and most causes appear to be related to [[antibodies]] against platelets. Very low platelet counts can lead to a bleeding diathesis and purpura. The T cell defect was initially shown to be an exaggerated [[interleukin-2]] response when T cells were cultured with platelets in vitro. Subsequently, this [[cytokine]] abnormality was shown by others to be responsible for many of the [[autoimmune]] mechanisms causing the disorder.).<ref>{{Cite journal | author = N Cooper| title = The pathogenesis of immune thrombocytopaenic purpura | journal = [[British Journal of Haematology]] | volume = 133 | pages = 364–374 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16643442 | issue = 4 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2141.2006.06024.x |display-authors=etal}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal | author = JW Semple| title = Differences in serum cytokine levels in acute and chronic autoimmune thrombocytopenic purpura: relationship to platelet phenotype and antiplatelet T-cell reactivity | journal = [[Blood (journal)|Blood]] | volume = 87 | pages = 4245–4254 | year = 1996 | pmid = 8639783 | issue = 10 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal | author = M Kuwana| title = Autoreactive T cells to platelet GPIIb-IIIa in immune thrombocytopenic purpura. Role in production of anti-platelet autoantibody | journal = [[J Clin Invest]] | volume = 102 | pages = 1393–1402 | year = 1998 | pmid = 9769332 | issue = 7 | doi = 10.1172/JCI4238 | pmc = 508987 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal | author = B Olsson| title = T-cell-mediated cytotoxicity toward platelets in chronic idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura | journal = [[Nature Medicine]] | volume = 9 | pages = 1123–1124 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12937414 | issue = 9 | doi = 10.1038/nm921 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal |vauthors=Stasi R, etal | title = Analysis of regulatory T cell changes in patients with idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura receiving B-cell depleting therapy with rituximab | journal = [[Blood (journal)|Blood]] | volume = 112 | pages = 1147–1150 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18375792 | issue = 4 | doi = 10.1182/blood-2007-12-129262 }}</ref> The importance of understanding the T cell defects in ITP is that novel therapies aimed at these cells may significantly benefit patients with ITP.
